    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, I've been doing a lot of HIIT lately and I keep hearing people talk about \"lactic acid buildup\" and that burning sensation in the muscles. Can you explain the actual biochemistry of how lactic acid is produced during high intensity work and how the body clears it out afterwards?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Absolutely, during high-intensity workouts, your body generates energy faster than your body can supply it. This leads to a shift from aerobic metabolism to anaerobic metabolism, where glucose is converted to lactic acid to keep the energy supply going. The lactic acid then enters your bloodstream and can cause that burning sensation in your muscles. Once the workout is over, your body will gradually convert the lactic acid back into glucose in your liver, a process known as the Cori cycle. This way, your body can use the lactic acid as an energy source again. So, while it may feel like a burning sensation, it's actually your body's way of dealing with the intense energy demands, and it's not the lactic acid causing the burn, but rather the buildup of hydrogen ions that contribute to the sensation.",
      "source": "target",
